availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: MS35 contains a collection of bardic poetry. It does not seem to be a duanaire devoted to the dynastic interests of a particular patron nor does it promote the output of a particular learned family. It may be a collection of highly regarded bardic poems for use in a bardic school.

Among these poems are six Classical panegyrics that are each associated with Scotland in some way, whether being by a possibly Scottish poet or addressed to a Scottish patron or both. These have been included in the corpus. Many of the poets and patrons involved were active in the 13th century, making the relevant texts some of the earliest items in the corpus in terms of composition if not in terms of scribal production.

summary.p: Poems 1 and 6 are attributed to Muireadhach Albanach Ó Dálaigh and are each addressed to an Earl of Lennox, Alun Óg (fl. 1214) and his son, Amhlaoibh Mór (d. 1217). Poems 2 and 3 are attributed in other manuscripts to Giolla Brighde Albanach, about whom not much is known, although his sobriquet implies at least a connection with Scotland. Both of these are to the Irish lord, Donnchadh Cairbreach Ó Briain (d. 1242). Poem 5 is attributed elsewhere to the Irish poet, Eochaidh Ua hEoghusa, but is addressed to Aonghas Mac Dhomhnaill (d. 1296), Lord of the Isles. Poem 4 is later than the others. Its author is unknown, but it is addressed to Sir Seumus Mac Dhomhnaill of Knockrinsay (d. 1626), the last lord of Islay from Clan Donald South.

All of these poems can be safely classified as bardic poetry. They adhere to Classical standards in terms of language and metrical form, they centre around a noble patron and the poet’s relationship with them, and they make use of literary allusions that are canonical within this genre.

Like ‘Fuaras aisgidh gan iarraidh’ (MS36.1), many of the poems transcribed focus explicitly on the obligations of patrons to pay poets. In fact, various permutations of this theme predominate in Poems 2, 3, 5, and 6, in which the poet is actively soliciting greater generosity from their patron. Poem 4, meanwhile, is about encouraging Seumas mac Mac Dhomhnaill to actively assert his right to the kingship of Ireland, with the implication that this was not his policy already. While it is possible that the implied context of any of these poems is a literary conceit, it still difficult to imagine any of them other than Poem 1 being directly commissioned by the patron. They come across instead as single communications within a more complex patron-poet relationship. Indeed, Poem 6 describes itself as a laoidh and makes reference to a pre-existing duan mholta (praise poem) that the poet composed for the same patron (qq. 19–21). For all that, just as in a commissioned praise poem, the poet’s more general purpose remains the exalting of their patron alongside reminding them of the standard of behaviour they should be following. Even the central demand for payment, indeed, is used as the jumping off point for praise of the patron’s wealth, previous generosity, and praiseworthiness.

physDesc.p: Other than erosion or loss of writing surface on particular pages, the physical aspects of this paper manuscript rarely present serious problems. A single scribe (Hand62) is responsible for all of the contents. These are set out conventionally, with one couplet per manuscript line, with each metrical line separated by multiple puncta.

There is one instance of a later hand adding text in the margin (p. 820.14, plus bottom margin). The hand looks modern and is writing in pencil. However, this does not seem to be intended as an insertion into the text. A re-agent seems to have been applied to an eroded area on the page and the marginal “addition” is a note of the text revealed by the re-agent.

supportDesc.foliation: Several pre-modern foliations are present, none of which seem to be by the main scribe.
supportDesc.condition: The sections of MS35 from which transcription has been made are generally in good condition where the writing surface survives, although there is some erosion of text towards the bottom of some pages (esp. p. 860), writing surface has been lost altogether from the bottom of pp. 628 and 629, and in general tight binding occasionally obscures initials.

layoutDesc.p: One couplet per manuscript line and a new quatrain indicated with an enlarged initial projected into the left-hand margin.

summary.p: As noted, it is not possible on the basis of present knowledge to place the production of this manuscript. The scribe's activity has been dated to the latter two thirds of the 17th century based on the dates of some of the poems he transcribes and his adherence to Classical standards in terms of language and orthography. The manuscript was part of the Stowe collection (Stowe Ir. MSS, 61) acquired by the Royal Irish Academy, meaning that it probably belonged to Charles O’Conor of Belanagare (ob. 1791).

langUsage.p: These poems are all in Classical Gaelic, with almost all characteristics explicable with reference to this dialect. More conservative features such as a distinctive accusative or synthetic verb forms in evidence throughout, although sometimes only sporadically. In an illustration of the stable flexibility of the Classical dialect, conservative features are most frequently encountered in Poem 4, which is the latest of the six texts. The orthography closely conforms to Classical norms and is distinguished by particularly punctilious (if sometimes hypercorrect) addition of length marks.

note.p: What looks like a correction in the lower margin in fact reads identically to the text it is meant to correct. The main text here seems to have been at some point difficult to read but was then improved by means of a chemical reagent. The "correction" may be a confirmation of the reading thus obtained, rather than an actual correction.
The first four quatrains of this poem have been lost in a physical chasm in the manuscript.

This could be "gort" (field) and be a line of panegyric relating to Amlaíb ("of the green fields of appletrees") or it could be a substantive use of "goirt" (hungry man) and refer to Muiredach in apposition ("the hungry man of the green bare of apples"), depending on how foreceful one takes the complaint in the poem to be.
